sions, forced displacement, environmental damage, loss of democratic freedom, and mass killings. Mónica M. Salas Landa uses the history of northern Veracruz to demonstrate how these state-led efforts reshaped the region's social and material landscapes, affecting what was and is visible. Relying on archival sources and ethnography, she uncovers a visual order of ongoing significance that was established through postrevolutionary projects and that perpetuates inequality based on imperceptibility.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aMural painting and decorationxPolitical aspectszMexico. 0aNation-buildingzMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aNational characteristics, Mexican, in artxPolitical aspectszMexico. 0aNationalism and artzMexicozVeracruz-Llave (State)xHistoryy20th century. 0aRuins, ModernxPolitical aspectszMexicozVeracruz-Llave (State). 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aMexican Revolution, Veracruz, indigenismo, Aesthetics, PEMEX, pyramid of Tajín, Totonac, Visual Culture, material culture, land reform, oil nationalismpre-Hispanic monuments, postrevolutionary Mexico, state-formation, nationalism, ruins studies, Latin American Studies, Smithsonian, Mexico's National School of Anthropology and History, PRI party, Affect Studies, Political Anthropology, Archaeology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079783140uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32871240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477328729423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477328729/original  a978-3-11-079783-1  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles